User story 3 - Finding authoritative and appropriately scaled data for analysis BHP Bilton is doing a desktop exercise to find out if a proposed mine site is within a particular jurisdiction to: - determine appropriate planning regulations and constraints (State/LGA interaction) - determine who has authority to grant mine licence (State interaction) In BHP GIS environment, a user zooms into the proposed mine site location to determine if the site is in State/Territory A or B. The user determines that the representation of the State Boundary data set she is using is too generalized a line. She therefore goes online to find a better representation. 1. The user searches for State Boundaries in the NSII and finds x data sets returned. 2. She filters out results based on custodian (looking for authoritative data sets) 3. For an authoritative data source she discovers that representations at 1:1m and 1:50K are available. 4. She selects the 25k version, checks the licence of the data to ensure it is appropriatre for her use and downloads it.

User story 2 - Flood risk reduction response and recovery (filter and link) A policy officer in a disaster management agency has been asked to provide the following information about a current flood event: - number of people affected by the flood - Which electorates are affected (state and Federal) - which jurisdictions are affected (and reponsible officers at each level) to commence the process of determining disaster grants A flood polygon has been defined. Overlay flood polygon on admin unit layers (filter data) - identify affected LGAs and electorates (discover data set by admin unit code) - with the identifiers of affected LGAs: query statistical data (ABS) to calculate required stats (link thematic data) - with the identifiers of affected LGAs: query relevant data sources to identify contact officers (link thematic data) - find SOP/policy legislation across jurisdiction

User story 1 - Policy analysis (find, filter and link) Government implements a policy at point in time. An analyst wants to measure and report on the success of policy initiative comparing before and after data for affected areas and report by LGA or locality. This requires retrieval of admin boundaries and relevant demographic data (stats units) for several points in time over the period of policy implementation. Steps 1. Define area of interest and identify the relevant admin units affected. 2. Select the boundaries to be used (depends of scale of analysis) and for relevant time period 3. Using the identifiers for the admin areas, find stats data for relevant points in time 4. Joins data to boundaries and conduct spatial analysis calculating an areal statistic for the affected areas at start midway and at end of policy period.

The generic administrative unit application schema. This includes administrative unit types that are not modeled in a more specialized schema. In many cases these manage specific administrative functions as delegated by a government unit, such as - catchment management authorities - school zones - police and law enforcement - fire and emergency services In other cases, the administrative unit, through still formally gazetted, is primarily ceremonial or informative with few or no administrative functions, such as - city, area, rural city, borough, town, - locality - shire, parish, hundred, division For any particular function it is expected that administrative units do not intersect or overlap. There will be a relationship with the government unit that is responsible for delegating the specific function, and there may be relationships with other administrative units. Examples: http://www.dtpli.vic.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0013/111316/Melbourne_v47.pdf http://www.health.vic.gov.au/regions/ http://www.mfb.vic.gov.au/About-Us/StationMap.html and select districts http://www.cfa.vic.gov.au/warnings-restrictions/find-your-fire-district/ http://vicwater.org.au/victorian-water-industry/catchment-management-authorities http://www.police.vic.gov.au/content.asp?Document_ID=7 http://melbourneschoolzones.com/ See also: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cadastral_divisions_of_Australia

The Class Model is a logical model of the software system under construction. Classes generally have a direct relationship to source code or other software artifacts that can be grouped together into executable components.
The System package contains the classes and artifacts which are being built or designed as part of the current model. The Frameworks package generally contains classes and components that have been designed and built earlier and are being reused as part of the current project.

The AreaHierarchy (AH) package contains common behavior model for any nested hierarchy of areas. The model addresses issues of navigation and cross referencing between hierarchies and the scoping of topology to versions of hierarchies. The hierarchy describes the topological relationships, not the (potentially multiple) alternative geometric descriptions of objects (see package AreaRepresentation).
